{"id": "EUVD-2021-31362", "enisaUuid": "cb1983bf-4bb4-3bbd-81ca-29a07ce7c966", "description": "Accepting arbitrary Subject Alternative Name (SAN) types, unless a PKI is specifically defined to use a particular SAN type, can result in bypassing name-constrained intermediates. Node.js < 12.22.9, < 14.18.3, < 16.13.2, and < 17.3.1 was accepting URI SAN types, which PKIs are often not defined to use. Additionally, when a protocol allows URI SANs, Node.js did not match the URI correctly.Versions of Node.js with the fix for this disable the URI SAN type when checking a certificate against a hostname. This behavior can be reverted through the --security-revert command-line option.", "datePublished": "2022-02-24T18:27:00", "dateUpdated": "2025-04-30T22:24:39", "baseScore": 7.4, "baseScoreVersion": "3.1", "baseScoreVector": "CVSS:3.1/AV:N/AC:H/PR:N/UI:N/S:U/C:H/I:H/A:N", "references": ["https://www.suse.com/security/cve/CVE-2021-44531.html", "https://advisories.mageia.org/CVE-2021-44531.html", "https://access.redhat.com/errata/RHSA-2022:4914", "https://www.debian.org/security/2022/dsa-5170", "https://access.redhat.com/errata/RHEA-2022:4925", "https://access.redhat.com/errata/RHEA-2022:5139", "https://access.redhat.com/errata/RHEA-2022:5221", "https://access.redhat.com/errata/RHEA-2022:5615", "https://access.redhat.com/errata/RHSA-2022:7044", "https://access.redhat.com/errata/RHSA-2022:7830", "https://access.redhat.com/errata/RHSA-2022:9073", "https://hackerone.com/reports/1429694", "https://nodejs.org/en/blog/vulnerability/jan-2022-security-releases/", "https://www.oracle.com/security-alerts/cpuapr2022.html", "https://security.netapp.com/advisory/ntap-20220325-0007/", "https://www.oracle.com/security-alerts/cpujul2022.html"], "aliases": ["CVE-2021-44531"], "assigner": "hackerone", "epss": 0.1, "enisaIdProduct": [{"id": "0fcecd2a-c7ec-382c-b660-5f80a5f079e7", "product": {"name": "Node"}, "product_version": "9.0 <9.*"}, {"id": "347663da-f3aa-3b73-8439-f505b67b7c16", "product":